fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
We lose no generality by assuming that s\in T. In the diagram
\usepackage {amsmath} \usepackage {amssymb} \usepackage {tikz-cd} \begin {tikzcd} \pi _1(T,s) \ar [r] \ar [d,swap,"a"] & \pi _1(S,s) \ar [d,"c"] \\\pi _1(U,p(s)) \ar [r,swap,"b"] & \pi _1(M,p(s)) \end {tikzcd}
the image of the arrow a is of finite index, since T is a finite étale covering, and the arrow b is surjective, since M\setminus U is of real codimension \geqslant 2. The image of the arrow c is thus of finite index.

